3. SYSTEM STRUCTURE

The  system  consists of different directories,  each  containing  directories
again, boards or files. You can change the actual directory using the command

               CHANGE DIRECTORY <DIRNAME>

Experienced users may use pathnames to choose a directory. The Command

               CHANGE DIRECTORY ..

(twice  the  period  instead  of <DIRNAME>)  places you  back  in  the  parent
directory. If you want to get into the root-directory, simply enter

               CHANGE DIRECTORY \

(backslash).  root-directory means the directory you were logged on,  when you
first entered MYSTERY-SYSTEMS at the actual call.


4. USER-CLASS

The  user class is a byte which determines which commands the user may use. To
use  a command it is obligate to have the corresponding class bit set in  ones
user class (refer to column CL in the SUMMARY OF MAIN COMMANDS). If the bit is
not set the message

               <CLASS VIOLATION!!>

will be displayed.  Further,  the user class determines the length of files the
user may upload (see -> VALUES.HLP).


5. ACCESS TO ITEMS

Wether a user may access an item (directory, board or file) belongs to his/her
relation  to  the  item and the permissions. Relations and  permissions  are
displayed in the directory. Downloads of files are not permitted if the user's
balance is zero. The balance is shown in the status.

5.1 RELATION

There is a relation between a user and each item in the system.  A user may be
the  item's  owner,  member  of  the item's owner's  group  or  none  of  both
(relation: ALL OTHERS).

5.2 PERMISSIONS

For  each  relation  a  group of permissions is given in  the  directory. Those
permissions  describe the possible access to the item relating to  the actual
user.

The following permissions are used:

          FILES          READ, WRITE, EXECUTE (RWE)
          BOARDS         READ, WRITE, ERASE/UPDATE (RWE)
          DIRECTORIES    CREATE, WRITE, ENTER (CWE)

CREATE  allows  the user to create new directories in that  directory.  Having
write  access  to  a directory means that the user may write  files  into  the
directory.  ENTER  allows  the user to enter the directory  using  the  CHANGE
DIRECTORY command.

5.3 BALANCE

The balance will be increased   by uploads of files or writing messages to bo-
ards and decreased   by downloads of files. If the balance is zero, downloads
of files are impossible.

5.4 EXAMPLE

The following is a directory entry:

NAME            LENGTH DATE     TIME     OWNER            GROUP OWN/GRP/ALL T

PIN.BRD         27300  12/07/87 14:58:00 SYSOP            0001  RWE RW- R-- B

The owner of this board is the SYSOP.  He may read the board,  write into  the
board, erase or update the board.

Users having the board's group bit set, belong to the same group as the board.
They may read from or write into the board.

All other users may read the board only.


6. A SHORT OVERVIEW TO FOR NEW USERS

6.1 HELP FUNCTIONS

For many commands you can get help using the command

               READ HELP <command>

To get the directory of the available helps type:

               DIR HELPS


6.2 BECOMING A NEW USER

To become a user of MYSTERY-SYSTEMS, you have to type

               WRITE NEWUSER <NAME> <PASSWORD>

Each  name  and password may have a maximum length of 20 characters.  For  the
name 8 bytes are significant only!  Legal characters for name and password are
letters  and digits!!  The new user account will be available within the  next
seven days.

6.3 LOGOUT

To leave the system, simply type LOGOUT.

6.4 READING ASCII-FILES OR BOARDS

To read an ASCII-file or a board just type:

               READ FILE <FILENAME>
               READ BOARD <BOARDNAME>

6.5 FILETRANSFER BY XMODEM- OR KERMIT-PROTOCOL

You  may download any file using XMODEM- or KERMIT-protocol.  To perform this,
type
              READ XFILE <FILENAME>
or
              READ KFILE <FILENAME>

To upload files using XMODEM- or KERMIT-protocol type

              WRITE XFILE <FILENAME>
or
              WRITE KFILE <FILENAME>


MYSTERY-SYSTEMS uses KERMIT in 8 bit mode (IMAGE MODE) as default.

6.6 WRITING ASCII-files OR WRITING TO BOARDS

To write a file or to a board type:

               WRITE FILE <FILENAME>
               WRITE BOARD <BOARDNAME>

Remark: if you have visitor-status (class 00), you can write to boards only.

To  finish the write-operation,  type *E in a new line.  The system will  then
exit  to  the editor's command level.  If you don't know the editor  commands,
type HELP if you are in the editor.

